== C &ndash; FPI Script ==
* [[C Programming|C]] - {{stage|50%|Oct 10, 2005}} - <small>([[:Category:C Programming|Index]])</small> <small>[[Computer programming/Structured programming|Structured]] ~ [[Computer programming/Imperative programming|Imperative]] ~ [[Computer programming/Procedural programming|Procedural]] </small>
: C is a [[w:System programming|system programming]] language and has a fairly simple syntax and a small set of keywords but with an extensive set of rules attached to those. It is also one of the most used languages. C is pretty much as low-level a programming language as you can get before [[Wikipedia:Assembly language|assembly language]]. C was originally designed to program operating systems - specifically, it was designed to implement [[Wikipedia:Unix|UNIX]]. It compiles to very small executables and it is used extensively in [[Embedded Systems|embedded systems]] with limited memory. C is the basis for, or has greatly influenced many modern programming languages such as Java, C#, PHP, and Python.

== [[Subject:C++|C++]] is a general purpose, multi-paradigm mid-level programming language ==
* [[C++ Programming]] - {{stage|75%}} - <small>[[Computer programming/Structured programming|Structured]] ~ [[Computer programming/Imperative programming|Imperative]] ~ [[Computer programming/Procedural programming|Procedural]] ~ [[Computer programming/Object oriented programming|Object oriented]]</small>
* [[C++ Programming As A Set Of Problems]]
* [[Understanding C++]]
* [[More C++ Idioms]] - {{stage|50%|Nov 24, 2007}}

== C# ==
* [[C Sharp Programming|C# Programming]] - {{stage|50%|May 9, 2007}}
: C# is a relatively new object-oriented programming language very similar to [[Java Programming|Java]] and is one of the four built-in languages for the [[w:Microsoft_.NET|.NET Framework]] by [[w:Microsoft|Microsoft]]. The [[w:Mono_development_platform|Mono Project]] has also implemented much of .NET for other Operating Systems, such as Linux, BSD and OS X.  <!-- what new paradigms? C# incorporates several new programming paradigms that are not found in other languages and directly supports several of the fab four's design patterns. --> C# incorporates its features from [[Subject:C++|C++]], Java and also addresses their shortcomings.
* [[Clojure]]
* [[Concurrent Clean]] - {{stage|00%|Jan 11, 2005}}
* [[Common Lisp|Common Lisp]] - {{stage|25%|Nov, 01 2005}}
* [[D Programming|D]] - {{stage|00%|Oct 10, 2005}} <small>[[Computer programming/Structured programming|Structured]] ~ [[Computer programming/Object oriented programming|Object oriented]] ~ [[Computer_programming/Functional_programming|Functional (under development)]]</small>
: D is a programming language created by [http://www.walterbright.com Walter Bright] and available at [http://www.digitalmars.com/d Digital Mars]. It's a [[Subject:C++|C++]] derivative with emphasis on execution efficiency, simple semantic models and safe features. D is a multi-paradigm language  featuring garbage collection and [[Computer_programming/Design_by_Contract|contracts]].  Support for functional programming is under development.  There is a [http://www.digitalmars.com/d/comparison.html comparison table] available to show some of the features of D compared to well-established ones.
* [[A Beginner's Guide to D|Learning to Program with D]] - {{stage|00%|Sep, 06 2006}}
* [[Delphi Programming|Delphi]] - {{stage|00%|Oct 10, 2005}}
* [[Eiffel programming|Eiffel]] - <small>[[Computer programming/Object oriented programming|Object oriented]] ~ [[Computer programming/Design_by_Contract|Design by contract]]</small>
:Eiffel is a pure real-world object-oriented language designed as such from the ground up in the early 1980s by Bertrand Meyer. It embodies several formal techniques, such as the use of assertions making them accessible to the programmer and designer in an integrated technique called design by contract, used to break down the functionality of software into cooperating modules (classes). The correct interaction of these modules is checked by the use of preconditions, postconditions, and class invariants, integrated with the exception handling mechanism. Eiffel incorporates an elegant design of multiple inheritance and generics.
*[[Elm programming language]]
: Elm is a strong-typed [[w:reactive functional programming|reactive functional programming]] language for declaratively creating graphical user interfaces. It compiles to Javascript so that programs can be shown in web browsers.
* [[Erlang Programming]] - {{stage|50%|29 Mar 2008}}
* [[Forth]] - {{stage|00%|Jan, 01 0000}}
* [[Fortran]] - {{stage|25%|Jan, 01 0000}}
* [[FPI Script]] - {{stage|00%|January 10, 2009}}
