[[Image:Küchenkräuter-1.jpg|right|thumb|Oregano (bottom) with rosemary and thyme]] {{spice}}
'''Oregano''' is a herb that is found in both [[Cookbook:Cuisine of the Mediterranean|Mediterranean]] and [[Cookbook:Cuisine of Mexico|Mexican cuisine]]. The leaves are used either fresh or dried, but the taste is stronger in the dried herb. The Mediterranean variety is mild in flavor, whereas its Mexican counterpart has a more earthly taste. It can be used with anything that has [[Cookbook:Tomato|tomato]] and in [[Cookbook:Salad Recipes|salads]], and is frequently used in [[Cookbook:Pizza|pizza]] toppings and guacamole.
Oregano is very similar to [[Cookbook:Marjoram|marjoram]], another herb from the same family, and is sometimes called ''wild marjoram'' or ''pot marjoram''. Oregano is stronger in flavor than marjoram, and marjoram is sweeter.
Oregano is often used in combination with [[Cookbook:Basil|basil]] in [[Cookbook:Cuisine of the Mediterranean|Mediterranean cuisine]].
{{Wikipedia|Oregano}}
